{"title_page": "The Wanderer (TV series)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Wanderer\n| genre                = Fantasy drama\n| creator              = [[Tom Gabbay]]<br />Roy Clarke\n| writer               = [[Roy Clarke]]\n| director             = [[Bob Mahoney (director)|Bob Mahoney]] <small>(episode 1)</small><br />Terry Marcel<br /><small>(episodes 2, 3 and 5)</small><br />Christopher King<br /><small>(episodes 4 and 9)</small><br />Alan Grint<br /><small>(episodes 6\u20138 and 12\u201313)</small><br />Rick Stroud<br /><small>(episodes 10 and 11)</small>\n| starring             = ''See [[#Cast|cast]] below''\n| composer             = Paul Hart<br />Joe Campbell<br />Bob Mahoney <small>(vocals)</small>\n| country              = [[United Kingdom]]<br />[[Germany]]<br />[[Spain]]\n| language             = [[English language|English]]\n| num_episodes         = 13\n| executive_producer   = [[Keith Richardson (television executive)|Keith Richardson]]<br />Tom Gabbay\n| producer             = Steve Lanning\n| location             = [[Leeds]] <small>([[England]])</small><br />[[Salzburg]] <small>([[Austria]])</small><br />[[Munich]] <small>(Germany)</small><br />[[Soria]] <small>(Spain)</small><br />[[London]] <small>(England)</small><br />[[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]] <small>(England)</small>\n| runtime              = 55 minutes (including adverts)\n| network              = [[Sky One]] <small>(United Kingdom)</small><br />[[ZDF]] <small>(Germany)</small><br />[[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]] <small>(Spain)</small>\n| picture_format       = [[Aspect ratio (image)|4:3]]\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| company            = FingerTip Films for [[ITV Yorkshire|Yorkshire Television]] and [[Sky UK|British Sky Broadcasting]]\n| first_aired          = 14 September\n| last_aired           = 7 December 1994\n}}\n'''''The Wanderer''''' is a fantasy drama television miniseries of a [[United Kingdom|British]] origin, first transmitted on [[Sky One]] from 14 September to 7 December 1994, and comprising 13 hour-long episodes.\n\nEvery episode brings a new adventure, and the story of long-ago brothers Adam and Zachary, Princess Beatrice, and Lady Clare slowly unfolds as the present-day Adam searches for the original Zachary's grave, a magic stone, and a lost book of power.\n\n==Premise==\nThe central characters of the programme were created, and its core format was developed, by [[Tom Gabbay]], who also served as executive producer of the series, which was filmed on locations in [[Austria]], [[Germany]], [[Spain]], and [[England]], including [[Chinatown, London|Chinatown]] in [[London]], [[Helmsley Castle]] and the [[Yorkshire Moors]], made by FingerTip Films (a partnership between [[Roy Clarke]], who wrote the scripts, and producer Steve Lanning) for [[ITV Yorkshire|Yorkshire Television]] with [[Sky UK|British Sky Broadcasting]] (United Kingdom), [[ZDF]] (Germany), and [[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]] (Spain). [[Bob Mahoney (director)|Bob Mahoney]] directed ''Rebirth'' is the first episode of the series.\n\nIn the [[United States]], ''The Wanderer'' was transmitted primarily in first-run syndication.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}}\n\n==Opening narration==\n'''Beginning for the first episode:'''\n{{quote|Long ago, at the end of the first millennium, twin brothers were born. In an appearance, the twins were identical in every way. But below the surface, the spirits were not at all alike. At the time of a passage into manhood, each twin was given his birthright. Identical stones lay in the hint of a shimmering sword, they were sent the hold a unique power... a power would lay opened the soul of a man who possessed it.}}\n\n'''Beginning from episodes 2 to 13:'''\n{{quote|Long ago, when the line between good and evil is clearly drawn. Twin brothers faced each other in battle, good with triumphant and the knight buried his brother. Now a thousand years later, the struggle continues...}}\n\n==Plot summary==\nThe shy multi-millionaire businessman Adam (\"the Wanderer\" of the programme's title) and his wicked twin brother Zachary (both played by Brown) are two former knights from the late 10th century during the [[Middle Ages]] at the end of the 1st millennium, both of whom have been [[born again]] (or [[Reincarnation|reincarnated]]) in the late 20th century. Zachary is after a complicated revenge on Adam, who killed him in the year [[Common Era|A.D.]] 1000, but much more is at stake than mere vengeance. As the turn of the 3rd millennium is approaching, people are growing more superstitious, and Zachary plans to use this for his own purpose. He needs his brother Adam dead, and Adam's death to be seen by witnesses, so he can pose as Adam [[Resurrection|resurrected]].\n\nThe other players in both time-zones are Zachary's beautiful but deadly companion Beatrice (played by Thomson), Adam's friend Godbold (in the present day a philosophically-minded [[plumber]] and [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] with a large beard, but once a [[hermit]] and [[monk]], played by Haygarth), and Adam's 10th century lover Lady Clare (played by Moore). She has come back in the present day as Clare, a high-spirited photographer, and she does not plan to lose her man a second time.\n\nWolfgang Mathias (played by Tausig) is Adam's personal assistant. Unfortunately for him, as he himself has no roots in the 10th century, he finds virtually everything about the Wanderer's world extremely confusing.\n\n==Cast==\n===Main characters===\n*[[Bryan Brown]] as Adam/Zachary\n*[[Tony Haygarth]] as Godbold\n*[[Kim Thomson]] as Beatrice\n*[[Deborah Moore]] as Clare\n*[[Otto Tausig]] as Wolfgang Mathias\n\n===Notable guest stars===\n*[[Tatjana Blacher]] as Inspector Mentzel <small>(''Rebirth'')</small>\n*Alexander Stebele as Forster <small>(''Mind Games'')</small>\n*[[Ann-Kathrin Kramer]] as Kiara <small>(''Mind Games'')</small>\n*[[August Schm\u00f6lzer]] as Kurt <small>(''Mind Games'')</small>\n*Jan Biczycki as Oskar <small>(''Bridges'')</small>\n*[[Uwe Ochsenknecht]] as Brandt <small>(''False Witness'')</small>\n*Felipe Jim\u00e9nez as Fatso <small>(''Clare'')</small>\n*Pedro Bea as Skinny <small>(''Clare'')</small>\n*Fernando Hilbeck as Clare's father <small>(''Clare'', ''Everybody Must Get Stoned'')</small>\n*Isabel Prinz as Clare's mother <small>(''Clare'', ''Everybody Must Get Stoned'')</small>\n*Debora Izaguirre as Loura <small>(''Everybody Must Get Stoned'')</small>\n*Pablo Scola as Pascual <small>(''Everybody Must Get Stoned'')</small>\n*[[Burt Kwouk]] as Ling Fat <small>(''A Dragon by Any Other Name'')</small>\n*Choy Ling Man as Sun Li <small>(''A Dragon by Any Other Name'')</small>\n*K.C. Leong as Wen <small>(''A Dragon by Any Other Name'')</small>\n*[[Mark Burns (actor)|Mark Burns]] as Sir Niles <small>(''Home'')</small>\n*[[Toby Sawyer]] as Mark <small>(''Home'')</small>\n\n==Episode listing==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No.\n! Episode\n! Director\n! Air Date\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Rebirth\" \n| Bob Mahoney\n| 14 September 1994   \n|-\n| 2\n| \"Mind Games\" \n|rowspan=\"2\"| Terry Marcel\n| 21 September 1994 \n|-\n| 3 \n| \"Bridges\" \n| 28 September 1994 \n|-\n| 4\n| \"False Witness\"  \n| Christopher King\n| 5 October 1994 \n|-\n| 5\n| \"Castle Takes Knight\"  \n| Terry Marcel\n| 12 October 1994   \n|- \n| 6\n| \"Clare\" \n|rowspan=\"3\"| Alan Grint\n| 19 October 1994 \n|-\n| 7\n| \"No Bull\" \n| 26 October 1994 \n|-\n| 8\n| \"Everybody Must Get Stoned\"  \n| 2 November 1994\n|-\n| 9\n| \"A Dragon by Any Other Name\" \n| Christopher King\n| 9 November 1994   \n|- \n| 10\n| \"See No Evil\" \n|rowspan=\"2\"| Rick Stroud\n| 16 November 1994 \n|-\n| 11\n| \"Waste Not, Want Not\"  \n| 23 November 1994  \n|-\n| 12\n| \"Home\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Alan Grint\n| 30 November 1994   \n|-\n| 13 \n| \"Knight Time\" \n| 7 December 1994     \n|}\n\n==Home media availability==\n[[ITV Studios|ITV Studios Home Entertainment]], owners of the copyright to ''The Wanderer,'' was not known to have released it on home media in any format as of the beginning of August 2014.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Middle Ages in popular culture]]\n*[[Reincarnation in popular culture]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0108987|title=The Wanderer}}\n\n{{Sky1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wanderer, The}}\n[[Category:Sky television programmes]]\n[[Category:1994 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1994 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:1990s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:British fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series by Yorkshire Television]]\n[[Category:1990s British television miniseries]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Wanderer\n| genre                = Fantasy drama\n| creator              = [[Tom Gabbay]]<br />Roy Clarke\n| writer               = [[Roy Clarke]]\n| director             = [[Bob Mahoney (director)|Bob Mahoney]] <small>(episode 1)</small><br />Terry Marcel<br /><small>(episodes 2, 3 and 5)</small><br />Christopher King<br /><small>(episodes 4 and 9)</small><br />Alan Grint<br /><small>(episodes 6\u20138 and 12\u201313)</small><br />Rick Stroud<br /><small>(episodes 10 and 11)</small>\n| starring             = ''See [[#Cast|cast]] below''\n| composer             = Paul Hart<br />Joe Campbell<br />Bob Mahoney <small>(vocals)</small>\n| country              = [[United Kingdom]]<br />[[Germany]]<br />[[Spain]]\n| language             = [[English language|English]]\n| num_episodes         = 13\n| executive_producer   = [[Keith Richardson (television executive)|Keith Richardson]]<br />Tom Gabbay\n| producer             = Steve Lanning\n| location             = [[Leeds]] <small>([[England]])</small><br />[[Salzburg]] <small>([[Austria]])</small><br />[[Munich]] <small>(Germany)</small><br />[[Soria]] <small>(Spain)</small><br />[[London]] <small>(England)</small><br />[[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]] <small>(England)</small>\n| runtime              = 55 minutes (including adverts)\n| network              = [[Sky One]] <small>(United Kingdom)</small><br />[[ZDF]] <small>(Germany)</small><br />[[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]] <small>(Spain)</small>\n| picture_format       = [[Aspect ratio (image)|4:3]]\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| company            = FingerTip Films for [[ITV Yorkshire|Yorkshire Television]] and [[Sky UK|British Sky Broadcasting]]\n| first_aired          = 14 September\n| last_aired           = 7 December 1994\n}}\n'''''The Wanderer''''' is a fantasy drama television miniseries of a [[United Kingdom|British]] origin, first transmitted on [[Sky One]] from 14 September to 7 December 1994, and comprising 13 hour-long episodes.\n\nEvery episode brings a new adventure, and the story of long-ago brothers Adam and Zachary, Princess Beatrice, and Lady Clare slowly unfolds as the present-day Adam searches for the original Zachary's grave, a magic stone, and a lost book of power.\n\n==Premise==\nThe central characters of the programme were created, and its core format was developed, by [[Tom Gabbay]], who also served as executive producer of the series, which was filmed on locations in [[Austria]], [[Germany]], [[Spain]], and [[England]], including [[Chinatown, London|Chinatown]] in [[London]], [[Helmsley Castle]] and the [[Yorkshire Moors]], made by FingerTip Films (a partnership between [[Roy Clarke]], who wrote the scripts, and producer Steve Lanning) for [[ITV Yorkshire|Yorkshire Television]] with [[Sky UK|British Sky Broadcasting]] (United Kingdom), [[ZDF]] (Germany), and [[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]] (Spain). [[Bob Mahoney (director)|Bob Mahoney]] directed ''Rebirth'' is the first episode of the series.\n\nIn the [[United States]], ''The Wanderer'' was transmitted primarily in first-run syndication.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}}\n\n==Opening narration==\n'''Beginning for the first episode:'''\n{{quote|Long ago, at the end of the first millennium, twin brothers were born. In an appearance, the twins were identical in every way. But below the surface, the spirits were not at all alike. At the time of a passage into manhood, each twin was given his birthright. Identical stones lay in the hint of a shimmering sword, they were sent the hold a unique power... a power would lay opened the soul of a man who possessed it.}}\n\n'''Beginning from episodes 2 to 13:'''\n{{quote|Long ago, when the line between good and evil is clearly drawn. Twin brothers faced each other in battle, good with triumphant and the knight buried his brother. Now a thousand years later, the struggle continues...}}\n\n==Plot summary==\nThe shy multi-millionaire businessman Adam (\"the Wanderer\" of the programme's title) and his wicked twin brother Zachary (both played by Brown) are two former knights from the late 10th century during the [[Middle Ages]] at the end of the 1st millennium, both of whom have been [[born again]] (or [[Reincarnation|reincarnated]]) in the late 20th century. Zachary is after a complicated revenge on Adam, who killed him in the year [[Common Era|A.D.]] 1000, but much more is at stake than mere vengeance. As the turn of the 3rd millennium is approaching, people are growing more superstitious, and Zachary plans to use this for his own purpose. He needs his brother Adam dead, and Adam's death to be seen by witnesses, so he can pose as Adam [[Resurrection|resurrected]].\n\nThe other players in both time-zones are Zachary's beautiful but deadly companion Beatrice (played by Thomson), Adam's friend Godbold (in the present day a philosophically-minded [[plumber]] and [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] with a large beard, but once a [[hermit]] and [[monk]], played by Haygarth), and Adam's 10th century lover Lady Clare (played by Moore). She has come back in the present day as Clare, a high-spirited photographer, and she does not plan to lose her man a second time.\n\nWolfgang Mathias (played by Tausig) is Adam's personal assistant. Unfortunately for him, as he himself has no roots in the 10th century, he finds virtually everything about the Wanderer's world extremely confusing.\n\n==Cast==\n===Main characters===\n*[[Bryan Brown]] as Adam/Zachary\n*[[Tony Haygarth]] as Godbold\n*[[Kim Thomson]] as Beatrice\n*[[Deborah Moore]] as Clare\n*[[Otto Tausig]] as Wolfgang Mathias\n\n===Notable guest stars===\n*[[Tatjana Blacher]] as Inspector Mentzel <small>(''Rebirth'')</small>\n*Alexander Stebele as Forster <small>(''Mind Games'')</small>\n*[[Ann-Kathrin Kramer]] as Kiara <small>(''Mind Games'')</small>\n*[[August Schm\u00f6lzer]] as Kurt <small>(''Mind Games'')</small>\n*Jan Biczycki as Oskar <small>(''Bridges'')</small>\n*[[Uwe Ochsenknecht]] as Brandt <small>(''False Witness'')</small>\n*Felipe Jim\u00e9nez as Fatso <small>(''Clare'')</small>\n*Pedro Bea as Skinny <small>(''Clare'')</small>\n*Fernando Hilbeck as Clare's father <small>(''Clare'', ''Everybody Must Get Stoned'')</small>\n*Isabel Prinz as Clare's mother <small>(''Clare'', ''Everybody Must Get Stoned'')</small>\n*Debora Izaguirre as Loura <small>(''Everybody Must Get Stoned'')</small>\n*Pablo Scola as Pascual <small>(''Everybody Must Get Stoned'')</small>\n*[[Burt Kwouk]] as Ling Fat <small>(''A Dragon by Any Other Name'')</small>\n*Choy Ling Man as Sun Li <small>(''A Dragon by Any Other Name'')</small>\n*K.C. Leong as Wen <small>(''A Dragon by Any Other Name'')</small>\n*[[Mark Burns (actor)|Mark Burns]] as Sir Niles <small>(''Home'')</small>\n*[[Toby Sawyer]] as Mark <small>(''Home'')</small>\n\n==Episode listing==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No.\n! Episode\n! Director\n! Air Date\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Rebirth\" \n| Bob Mahoney\n| 14 September 1994   \n|-\n|